<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="73" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1440,151,1392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,372,151,177]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">Etymology:—</emphasis>
Species epithet is named for Dr. Rex Lowe, faculty member of Bowling Green State University and University of 
<collectingRegion box="[499,612,188,214]" country="United States of America" name="Michigan" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">Michigan</collectingRegion>
Biological Station, who made the two collections from Bryant’s Bog in 1969 and 2008 and whose support is hereby acknowledged and who has been an inspiration to both CLG and JPK.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[198,1102,298,325]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1440,151,1392]" box="[198,1102,298,325]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,390,298,324]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">Distribution:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Graeff et Kociolek" authorityYear="2012" box="[390,560,299,324]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rexii">
<emphasis box="[390,560,299,324]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">Frustulia rexii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is present in Bryant’s Bog in 
<collectingRegion box="[909,1024,299,325]" country="United States of America" name="Michigan" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">Michigan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1036,1098,299,325]" name="United States of America" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">USA</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="73" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1440,151,1392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,403,335,361]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">Observations:—</emphasis>
The morphotype of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lange-Bertalot" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[639,782,336,361]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[639,782,336,361]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Jones Lake in 
<collectingRegion box="[1026,1203,336,362]" country="United States of America" name="North Carolina" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">North Carolina</collectingRegion>
illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P." pageId="11" pageNumber="73" refId="ref8533" refString="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P. (2011) Diatoms of North America. The Freshwater Flora of Waterbodies of the Atlantic Coastal Plain. In: Lange-Bertalot, H. (Ed) Iconographia Diatomologica. A. R. G. Ganter Verlag K. G., Ruggell, 916 pp." type="book" year="2011">Siver &amp; Hamilton (2011</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 140) is highly morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Graeff et Kociolek" authorityYear="2012" box="[921,1004,373,398]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rexii">
<emphasis box="[921,1004,373,398]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. rexii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The Jones Lake specimens share a number of interesting morphological features with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Graeff et Kociolek" authorityYear="2012" box="[756,839,409,434]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rexii">
<emphasis box="[756,839,409,434]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. rexii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
not seen in most other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1245,1355,409,434]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1245,1355,409,434]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">Frustulia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both have strongly rhomboid valves with a central area bordered on either side by a row of slightly transapically expanded areolae and a collection of unorganized poroids at the centre (
<bibRefCitation author="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P." box="[1002,1286,483,509]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" refId="ref8533" refString="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P. (2011) Diatoms of North America. The Freshwater Flora of Waterbodies of the Atlantic Coastal Plain. In: Lange-Bertalot, H. (Ed) Iconographia Diatomologica. A. R. G. Ganter Verlag K. G., Ruggell, 916 pp." type="book" year="2011">Siver &amp; Hamilton 2011</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 140, fig. 2). At the external apices, the areolae of both groups of specimens form a uniquely shaped unornamented area, similar to a four-leaf clover, because the rows of relatively small areolae nearest the raphe end abruptly near the end of the raphe. The longitudinal ribs of both groups are robust and strongly constricted at the central nodule (
<bibRefCitation author="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P." box="[343,639,630,656]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" refId="ref8533" refString="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P. (2011) Diatoms of North America. The Freshwater Flora of Waterbodies of the Atlantic Coastal Plain. In: Lange-Bertalot, H. (Ed) Iconographia Diatomologica. A. R. G. Ganter Verlag K. G., Ruggell, 916 pp." type="book" year="2011">Siver &amp; Hamilton 2011</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 140, fig. 1). The relationship between the helictoglossa and longitudinal ribs is also similar: where the longitudinal ribs attach angularly to the helictoglossa, but in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lange-Bertalot" baseAuthorityYear="2001" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
morphotype, the longitudinal ribs appear to widen much more noticeably before tapering into the helictoglossa (
<bibRefCitation author="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P." box="[319,602,740,766]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" refId="ref8533" refString="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P. (2011) Diatoms of North America. The Freshwater Flora of Waterbodies of the Atlantic Coastal Plain. In: Lange-Bertalot, H. (Ed) Iconographia Diatomologica. A. R. G. Ganter Verlag K. G., Ruggell, 916 pp." type="book" year="2011">Siver &amp; Hamilton 2011</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 140, figs 5 and 6). Close examination of a low magnification SEM suggests that the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lange-Bertalot" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[360,507,777,802]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[360,507,777,802]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
morphotype (
<bibRefCitation author="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P." box="[678,968,777,803]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" refId="ref8533" refString="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P. (2011) Diatoms of North America. The Freshwater Flora of Waterbodies of the Atlantic Coastal Plain. In: Lange-Bertalot, H. (Ed) Iconographia Diatomologica. A. R. G. Ganter Verlag K. G., Ruggell, 916 pp." type="book" year="2011">Siver &amp; Hamilton 2011</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 140, fig. 1) might also possess the abruptly widening longitudinal ribs seen in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Graeff et Kociolek" authorityYear="2012" box="[662,744,814,839]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rexii">
<emphasis box="[662,744,814,839]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. rexii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
near the apices.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1440,151,1392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">
The Michigan and North Carolina specimens share many morphological similarities. Regardless of the degree of morphological similarity between the Michigan and North Carolina specimens, distinguishing both populations from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lange-Bertalot" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[362,505,925,950]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[362,505,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most important. Indeed, LM and SEM illustrations of specimens identified as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lange-Bertalot" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[183,326,961,986]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[183,326,961,986]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its morphotype by 
<bibRefCitation author="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P." box="[604,899,961,987]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" refId="ref8533" refString="Siver, P. A. &amp; Hamilton, P. (2011) Diatoms of North America. The Freshwater Flora of Waterbodies of the Atlantic Coastal Plain. In: Lange-Bertalot, H. (Ed) Iconographia Diatomologica. A. R. G. Ganter Verlag K. G., Ruggell, 916 pp." type="book" year="2011">Siver &amp; Hamilton (2011)</bibRefCitation>
share morphological similarities in their ribs, helictoglossa, valve shape, and areolae with our specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Graeff et Kociolek" authorityYear="2012" box="[882,963,998,1023]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rexii">
<emphasis box="[882,963,998,1023]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. rexii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, LM images of specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lange-Bertalot" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[151,296,1035,1060]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[151,296,1035,1060]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<typeStatus box="[415,466,1035,1061]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">type</typeStatus>
material from 
<collectingCountry box="[646,737,1035,1061]" name="Finland" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">Finland</collectingCountry>
showing noticeably curved longitudinal ribs and an offset central nodule as well as a lack of abruptly widening longitudinal ribs near the apices, combined with apices that lack circumradiating striae (
<bibRefCitation author="Lange-Bertalot, H." box="[532,787,1108,1134]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" refId="ref7748" refString="Lange-Bertalot, H. (2001) Navicula sensu stricto, 10 genera separated from Navicula sensu lato Frustulia. In: Lange- Bertalot, H. (Ed), Diatoms of Europe. A. R. G. Ganter Verlag K. G., Ruggell, 526 pp." type="book" year="2001">Lange-Bertalot, 2001</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 128), suggest the Atlantic Coastal Plain specimens are not 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lange-Bertalot" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[247,399,1145,1170]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="krammeri">
<emphasis box="[247,399,1145,1170]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. krammeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Further examination of these specimens could be used to determine whether the Michigan and North Carolina specimens belong to the same species or two distinct but similar species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1440,151,1392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Graeff et Kociolek" authorityYear="2012" box="[198,370,1219,1244]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rexii">
<emphasis box="[198,370,1219,1244]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">Frustulia rexii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a species that has been commonly collected by researchers in northern Michigan over several decades but not immediately recognized as a unique species. 
<bibRefCitation author="Patrick, R. &amp; Reimer, C. W." box="[989,1289,1256,1282]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" refId="ref8080" refString="Patrick, R. &amp; Reimer, C. W. (1966) The diatoms of the United States. Volume 1. Fragilariaceae, Enotiataceae, Achnanthaceae, Naviculaceae. Monograph of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, Philadelphia, 688 pp." type="book" year="1966">Patrick &amp; Reimer (1966)</bibRefCitation>
included an illustration of a specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pfitzer" authorityYear="1871" baseAuthorityName="Ehrenb." baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[485,652,1293,1318]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rhomboides">
<emphasis box="[485,652,1293,1318]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. rhomboides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[723,820,1292,1318]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">England</collectingCountry>
that mirrors the strongly rhomboid valve shape of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Graeff et Kociolek" authorityYear="2012" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rexii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. rexii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Graeff et Kociolek" authorityYear="2012" box="[393,475,1329,1354]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rexii">
<emphasis box="[393,475,1329,1354]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. rexii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Michigan were likely given the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pfitzer" authorityYear="1871" baseAuthorityName="Ehrenb." baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[993,1160,1329,1354]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Amphipleuraceae" genus="Frustulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="rhomboides">
<emphasis box="[993,1160,1329,1354]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="73">F. rhomboides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to the frequent use of 
<bibRefCitation author="Patrick, R. &amp; Reimer, C. W." box="[182,474,1366,1392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="73" refId="ref8080" refString="Patrick, R. &amp; Reimer, C. W. (1966) The diatoms of the United States. Volume 1. Fragilariaceae, Enotiataceae, Achnanthaceae, Naviculaceae. Monograph of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, Philadelphia, 688 pp." type="book" year="1966">Patrick &amp; Reimer (1966)</bibRefCitation>
for the identification of North American diatom species.
</paragraph>
